Crag Path: La Palma - Campanarios de Jedey - Aguja Campanario
Comment: One of the most beautiful routes I've ever done. It's just unbelievable, how astonishing is the place. Some rocks are not so stable, but you can still trust them. Even though the approach is not easy, it's totally worth it.

Crag Path: La Palma - Campanarios de Jedey - Aguja Sur
Comment: Great route, very slab style. Getting to the first bolt is sketchy because of the falling rocks, but once you are at the actual wall, the rock is super solid. I enjoyed it a lot, very recommended.

Crag Path: Tenerife - South - Arico Arriba - Los Pinos
Comment: Definitely not a 5c or 5+. More a 6a than anything else. If you are looking for something entry level, I wouldn't recommend it.

Crag Path: Tenerife - South - Arico Arriba - Los Pinos
Comment: Rest it properly after a first attempt and could send it knowing the beta, even though it's a hard 6b+, very boulder style.

Crag Path: Tenerife - South - Arico Arriba - Los Pinos
Comment: Wanted to try this route since it was looking so nice from the bottom, but couldn't read it properly between the 2nd and 3rd bolts.

Crag Path: Tenerife - South - Arico Arriba - Los Pinos
Comment: Great route, but sketchy in the first movements, specially being close to the floor. Anyway, interesting route and recommended.

With: Ana Mestre,  Andreu Farré,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Janey L,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: I wasn't feeling so confident in this route. Even though I liked it, there are some unstable rocks and some polished holes.

With: Ana Mestre,  Andreu Farré,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Janey L,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: After two years without coming to this sector, I was able to repeat this route "on sight" since I wasn't remembering a thing. Cool route with an strange last movement.

With: Ana Mestre,  Andreu Farré,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Janey L,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: Last year I was able to onsight this route, but this time was another story. Anyway, incredible route. Very well recommended.

With: Ana Mestre,  Andreu Farré,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Janey L,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: Fun route with a continuous climbing for the most of the route and a roof in the end. Physical last part but good hands.

With: Ana Mestre,  Andreu Farré,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Janey L,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: Great chimney and very enjoyable! Very recommended and easy if you climbed chimneys in the past.

With: Andreu Farré,  Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Quim Picó Mora,  Janey L
Comment: After years of the first attempt, I tried again with better performance but not enough. A pretty complex slab.

With: Andreu Farré,  Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Quim Picó Mora,  Janey L
Comment: Pumpy route with great hand holes. Fun one!

With: Andreu Farré,  Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Quim Picó Mora
Comment: Long and fun route. Recommended!

With: Andreu Farré,  Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Quim Picó Mora
Comment: Great warm-up route with some great first movements. Only 4 bolts, so be aware.
Top slab in the first three bolts and easy-going rest of the route. Great one!
Done did as a second pitch coming from the RIP route (6a). Fun dihedral, recommended!
Great route, super fun! Interesting movements, and great to climbing. Recommended!
Easy route, with the most complex part between 1st and 2nd bolts, but all good.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Sud-Est - Gorros - La Magdalena superior
Comment:
My first multi-pitch route! Great experience and excited to start knowing how all this world works.

Not sure if this route is the one that I did, because I was looking for a 6a+ that wasn't in TheCrag. Anyway, nice long enough route with some nice movements.
Tried this route knowing that it was a 6b, not a 6c. And also, the crag from the crux was pretty wet. However, very enjoyable route!
Great route with a doable overhanging part. A different and special route in the sector. Recommended.
Nice and fun start, where the most difficult part is. Very technical with small footholds, but you can trust them.
Fun route where the crux is in the first part, where feet trust is crutial. Since all the rest is pretty trivial, I would say is a 6a+.
Great route with some nice crags to use, and an interesting movement post first anchor. Good sensations.
Great route, long enough. I climbed it the day after it rained and there were some more difficult parts, but nothing crazy.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Sector Clàssic - Biceps power
Comment: Interesting and nice sit start with a high heel hook. Couldn't handle it. After that, it looks much easier and similar to the "Te lo dije" boulder.

Very interesting start with a locked hook. Couldn't finish because topping this is hard since no hold was found on the top. Also, had to stop all of a sudden after an injury during the last session try.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Sector Clàssic - Biceps power
Comment: Tiny hand and foot holds, as expected. Could send it because I'm basically tall; it would be much harder if it weren't the case.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Sector Clàssic - Biceps power
Comment: My first big dyno in a Boulder rock. Scary but fun at the same time.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Sector Clàssic - Biceps power
Comment: Sketchy start with not-so-good start foot holds. The rest, though, is a nice diagonal traverse to the top.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Sector Clàssic - Soldador universal
Comment: I thought that the hardest part was the sit start, but it was actually the end with 3 sloper holds.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
Comment: Second attempt of the day with the quick draws set. I knew the theory from the last attempt but I was as fresh as I should, so I ended up super tired. Anyway, happy of today's performance. I feel the send closer.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
Comment: New day attempting this route, and very happy of the performance meanwhile setting the quick draws. I fell because I went to the right in the crux movement when it wasn't left, but I wasn't able to remember.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
Comment: Could send it in the second go! Knowing how to handle the tricky part helped a lot and made everything much simpler.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
Comment: Great second pitch, where everything is from the first to the second bolt. Pretty small holds where you have to go out of the overhanging part.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
Comment: Done the first pitch for going to the second one. No problem at all but for being a 4, since I was expecting something super easy, it has some small holds that shouldn't be in a 4.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
Comment: Great and super recommended warm-up route in the crag. Very intuitive and long enough route.

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 88. La Lluna
Comment: Two movements, both with the left hand, from the start with a high heel hook that feels super uncomfortable in the first try, but could make it in the 3rd one!

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 82. La Travesia
Comment: Just couldn't start. The start (where the whole boulder is) is completely unknown to me.

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 82. La Travesia
Comment: This boulder is so cool! With powerful movements in the first half and then a high mantle that I was able to handle with an extra confidence that I didn't have last year.

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 26. Totxo del Boig
Comment: I tried it a year ago and tried again, this time with the luck of being able to send (my first 6C!). You just need to be pretty confident in the last movement.

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 67. El Petit
Comment: Great sit-start boulder. Not easy at all, with the first powerful movement and then so sketchy sloper top hands.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Petit Paradís - El techo
Comment: Interesting boulder where being strong is vital to mantle the "techo". Not mentally prepared to do it, to be honest.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Petit Paradís - El techo
Comment: Pretty dirty hand holds were you should try the mantle, and a very uncomfortable sit start. Not very recommended.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Petit Paradís - Jonny Dawes
Comment: Very sketchy slab boulder with tiny footholds. High handholds were dirtier than I would like.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Petit Paradís - Jonny Dawes
Comment: Boulder of only one movement from the sit start. Not super hard. The rest is just keeping focus because it's a tall boulder.

Crag Path: Can Boquet - Petit Paradís - Jonny Dawes
Comment: Hard slab with pretty nonexistent holds for being a 5+. Also, Boulder is quite dirty, so it's not recommended.

This was actually the second attempt because in the first attempt I skipped the last but one bolt by mistake, making the route much easier. In this proper attempt, I could do all the low part but couldn't handle the physical part. Will come back!
Send it! The first 7b! However, after talking with Marc and doing his try, it's not a 7b. Maximum a 7a. So, even though it's the first 7b, I want to do more to confirm the grade
Used this route, which maximum 6a+, to warm-up. It's just a few movements slightly complex in the top because they are long but good hands overall.
Tried for the last time of the day and unbelievably I couldn't send it because I grabbed the last hole but I was so pumped that I couldn't clip. So frustrating!
Better second attempt but get lost in the last movement, as the first time. But, I studied better, and I get the idea, so let's see next time.
First attempt to this 7a+ (or 7b depending on the guidebook) and felt super good. Could handle the whole thing but felt around the anchor, where the most complex part is.
I could send it in my second attempt. Knowing all the moves help, but it's definitely a tough 6b+.
Pretty intense 6b+, not gonna lie, I could complete the route but definitely you need to read it properly to send it.
Used for warm-up, and pretty easy let me say. It's true that I used the big rock from the bottom, so made it easier.

With: David Aleu Moseguí,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Janey L,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Very cool route, top tier, the best one from the whole weekend. Very tiny foot holds with great technique. I really enjoyed it!

With: David Aleu Moseguí,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Janey L,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment:
Done just the first pitch, the 6a. It's a super easy route, very enjoyable, more a 5/5+.
1:[6a]

With: Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  David Aleu Moseguí,  Janey L
Comment: Top tier route! Even though the first bolt is extremely far away, the rest of the route is such beautiful. Very intuitive, and enjoyable!

With: Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  David Aleu Moseguí,  Janey L
Comment: Pretty cool route, very enjoyable! Slippery footholds specially at the beginning though.

With: Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  David Aleu Moseguí,  Janey L
Comment: Probably the conditions weren't the best, since it was fully sun and it was around 35°C. I also thought that was a 7a, so harder than expected.

With: Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  David Aleu Moseguí,  Janey L
Comment: Cool route, but pretty slippery. Not sure if I enjoyed the route that much. Not so recommended.

With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: After a last attempt for the day, I could finally send it after the whole day working on the route. Perfectly optimized the start and great flow.

With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Much better management in the first part, but fell in the middle of the crux due to lack of skin.

With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: First attempt of the day after a proper session the other day. Great attempt, close for the send.

With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: In the 2nd attempt of the day and the 4th in total, I could send it after a proper optimization of the first part.

With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: After 2 attempts the first day, I tried again for the first time in the day. I was not so optimal in the first bolts so I was pretty tired in the crux, and I fell.

With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Fun, quick and short route with a decent intense movement between the first and second bolt.

With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: After trying it the other day, I tried again today with a clearer idea and already warm-up, and it was all fine!

With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Easy route to start route with really good hands. Extremely short route with 2 bolts and the anchor.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os
Comment: Great second attempt where I fall in the difficult part, just when you need to change the wall from one to the other one. The rest I did it super great!

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os
Comment: Great route. Two different types of climbing in the same route. Not single difficult movements, but all together it's a 6c+

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os
Comment: First climb of the day, and after several weeks without climbing. Typical Montserrat where you have to trust a lot, which I wasn't.

Crag Path: Costa Brava - Cova de sa Gatera
With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Andreu Farré,  Genís
Comment: Last attempt, after a proper rest, but didn't know how to handle the movements to get to the bavaresa.

Crag Path: Costa Brava - Cova de sa Gatera
With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Andreu Farré,  Genís
Comment: Third and best attempt where I almost get a good hand next to the bavaresa, but fell from there.

Crag Path: Costa Brava - Cova de sa Gatera
With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Andreu Farré,  Genís
Comment: Second attempt, after feeling more confident with better handling of the first movements but didn't know how to get to the bavaresa.

Crag Path: Costa Brava - Cova de sa Gatera
With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Andreu Farré,  Genís
Comment: First ever attempt at a DWS route and, obviously, I got pretty scared and I had to jump after the first movements.

Crag Path: Sant Llorenc de Munt - La Mola - Font Soleia - Paret Gran
Comment:
With the first pitch set up, I've tried a proper second attempt, knowing all the movements and happy about the result. However, I was pretty pumped after the whole day and couldn't send it.
1:[7a]

Crag Path: Sant Llorenc de Munt - La Mola - Font Soleia - Paret Gran
Comment:
I was looking for a 7a in La Paret Gran and I ended up trying the first pitch of this great route. Super cool, recommended!
1:[7a]

Crag Path: Sant Llorenc de Munt - La Mola - Font Soleia - Paret Gran
Comment: Red-pointed in the second attempt, after having a super clear idea of how the route should be climbed and enjoyed it a lot!

Crag Path: Sant Llorenc de Munt - La Mola - Font Soleia - Paret Gran
Comment: Not a very efficient attempt, where I ended up super pumpy and fell just on the anchor sadly.

Crag Path: Sant Llorenc de Munt - La Mola - Font Soleia - Els Diedres
Comment: Great route, with a fun start with the help of the tree. Decent easy-to-read route.

Crag Path: Sant Llorenc de Munt - La Mola - Font Soleia - Els Diedres
Comment: What a strange start, with no clear idea of what was needed. It's true that was the first one of the day, but no recommended route.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
With: Quim Picó Mora,  Andreu Farré,  Genís,  Xavier Piqueras
Comment: What a route. Not trivial to read, at least to me, and pretty pumpy. A decent 6c+. Cool route, will try again at some point.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Mirador
With: Quim Picó Mora,  Andreu Farré,  Genís,  Xavier Piqueras
Comment:
Done the first 2 pitches, and not completing the rest due to missing quickdraws, even though I had 16 with me. Super cool route, very recommended.
1:
2:
Much better second attempt where I almost send it. Just 1 movement and a half away from the last good hand and the route was over. Happy! Excited to try again another day.
Good first attempt until the 2nd bolt, where I could handle the left hand movement to the good hand. Start easy but with hands that are super painful to hold even though they are good.
Second attempt with the beta clear and I could handle the first crux but not the second because I made a mistake and went with the wrong hand. Cool route, but for another day.

Super cool route with two long movements in the crux, between 3rd and 4th bolt, and then between 4th and 5th bolt. The first bolt is pretty far away. I couldn't on-sight it because the crux movements are intense and not super intuitive.
Crux in the 3rd bolt, where I fell because I was so lost in the first route of the day. Good for warm-up.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: First attempt to this route. The beginning is easy because it's the shared part with the 6b, but the crux is pretty hard and very intense. Didn't know how to handle it and go to the 6b to finish the route.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: And today, being super fresh and with the beta super clear, I could send it in the first go of the day. Nice!

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Mirador
Comment:
Did the first pitch, 5+, as the easy warm-up of the day. Very cool. Small overhanging in the middle with incredible hands.
1:

Crag Path: Margalef - Cami de la Presa - Ca La Marta
Comment: As mentioned in other comments, fantastic and great route! Sketchy and difficult to read start, specially from the ground until the second bolt. Later on it's very constant and with good holds when it's slightly overhanging. I fell in last part of the route in my on-sight attempt, and very happy about it!

Crag Path: Margalef - Cami de la Presa - Ca La Marta
Comment: The hardest part is the first bolt, the rest is pretty doable. The 6a is all in this initial part. Recommended to clip the second one directly if you have an stick.

Crag Path: Margalef - Cami de la Presa - El Tobogan
Comment:
There's a comment in the route in TheCrag that says that there are some missing holes that makes the route harder to 7a. Being honest, I don't think that's case because I felt the route as a correct 6b+ slab.

The beginning all easy, with a lot of space between bolts and the last part where the 6b+ is. Very technical and cool movements.

Crag Path: Margalef - Cami de la Presa - El Tobogan
Comment: Very comfortable route except for the last bolt, where the whole 5c is. Not super difficult but the change is big compared to the rest of the route.

Crag Path: Margalef - Cami de Sant Salvador - Cami De L'Ermita
Comment: Very cool route, super complete. However, more pumpy that I was expecting. Maybe trying to climb this on June doesn't help. Cool but far to be sendable.

Crag Path: Margalef - Cami de Sant Salvador - Cami De L'Ermita
Comment: Fun traverse to the left with an overhanging start with artificial hands. Once the route goes straight, it's much easier.

Crag Path: Margalef - Cami de Sant Salvador - Cami De L'Ermita
Comment: Second and third bolts very pumpy and where the whole 6b+ is. Not gonna lie that overhanging with pockets is not my style at all. But happy to try it at least.

Crag Path: Margalef - Cami de Sant Salvador - Cami De L'Ermita
Comment: Easy but not trivial start for a 5+, but the rest is all easy.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: I almost send it! I could handle the crux movements, after a proper rest in the good hands, but I get lost in the final movements to the final jug. A pitty but this one will be sent for sure next day.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: Pretty good first attempt where I could handle the whole thing until the crux, when it was hard to read it properly of how to place the right hand correctly in the bad hold.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Mirador
Comment: Great and long warm-up route. Nothing complex, pretty straightforward.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: After 2 years of the first and only try, today I wanted to see if my technique and endurance improved and well well, a lot! What a great route! I enjoyed it at maximum!

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: Finally I could send this nice route! After a first attempt where I got the crux movements, I could do the whole thing from the ground.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: First attempt of the day after months without retrying this route. Much better and more optimized during the first part. But I forgot the crux movements and I fell.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Mirador
Comment: Super fun and long route. Very intuitive and easy to run. Top tier route for warm up.
After a long time since the last and first ascent, happy to repeat the route on-sight. Very cool route with fun movements.

After a lot of months, I tried this route again and I'm pretty happy about the result since I could do the crux from the ground. However, I was so pumped that I couldn't handle the last two bolts. A pitty but happy anyways!
Great warm-up route. A bit polish, but handleable.

Crag Path: Garraf - Pas de la Mala Dona - Bauma
Comment: Great and perfect second attempt where all the movements just worked. Super happy how I read everything. The reality though is that, even though I touched the anchor twice, for security reasons I had to grab the anchor quickdraw. I know it's not a "clean" send, but I'm gonna consider it this time because i had the anchor just at my head level.

Crag Path: Garraf - Pas de la Mala Dona - Bauma
Comment: Great route! At the first attempt I get a bit lost at the very beginning and I get pumped and I couldn't handle the rest and I fell. However I read the movements pretty good knowing it was on sight.

Crag Path: Garraf - Pas de la Mala Dona - Neska Polita
Comment: Super fan overhanging, with really good hands, on the top. Very recommended route!

With: Genís,  Ferran Noguera,  Andreu Farré,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Fun route, really good hands and a nice mantle at the top.

With: Genís,  Ferran Noguera,  Andreu Farré,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: What a crazy boulder, not my style, not sure how to do it.

With: Genís,  Ferran Noguera,  Andreu Farré,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: At the beginning it felt completely impossible but I could handle until the middle, managing the first dyno. Cool boulder.

With: Genís,  Ferran Noguera,  Andreu Farré,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Without doubt, the funniest boulder in the crag. Also, super physical. You forearm ends up completely destroyed, recommended to try it with a hoodie.

With: Genís,  Ferran Noguera,  Andreu Farré,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Sketchy start where balance is important. Once you get your right hand in the top right, use a low right foot to match the top and place a high heel hook.

With: Genís,  Ferran Noguera,  Andreu Farré,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Great footholds at the beginning with a pinch in the top left that help you do the mantle.

With: Genís,  Ferran Noguera,  Andreu Farré,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Nice boulder. Great left initial hands with an small crimp before the top.

With: Genís,  Ferran Noguera,  Andreu Farré,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Great warm-up boulder. Technical but only 3 movements.

What a route! What a fantastic route! I've done the first pitch, 6c, and it's all very constant except for last bolt where the crux is. It's pretty painful that the crux is in the last movement.

Crag Path: Cavallers - dreta de la presa - Drinking
With: Andreu Farré,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ferran Noguera,  Xavier Piqueras
Comment: Cool route, with the most sketchy movement in the top. Nothing crazy, an expected 6b. I had an stupid but simple slip in the middle of the route.

What a crazy route. The extension made at early 2024 through the second overhanging is ridiculously difficult. I tried and sent different 7a routes and I haven't seen anything closer. All the group tried and no one could handle. The rest is a 6c+/7a.
Better ascent in the second go but all my power went out in the 7th bolt. Sad because I know how to read it and I know all the movements but send it feels still far away.

First attempt, pretty exploratory. The first block looks scary but it's pretty doable. The crux is at 65% of the route, with very long movements. I think it's sendable since every movement is doable, but very pumpy overall.
Great route, a very representative route of the crag, very Matxos style. Watch out between the 3rd and 4th bolt, where the distance is huge.

Crag Path: Sant Llorenc de Munt - La Mola - El Diafragma

Crag Path: Sant Llorenc de Munt - La Mola - El Diafragma
With: Janey L,  Genís,  Andreu Farré,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Marc Klingenberg,  Elena Ruiz
Comment: Exploratory go, trying to understand each movement. Difficult route, very finger demanding and large movements.

With: Janey L,  Genís,  Andreu Farré,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Marc Klingenberg,  Elena Ruiz

Crag Path: Sant Llorenc de Munt - La Mola - El Diafragma
With: Janey L,  Genís,  Andreu Farré,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Marc Klingenberg,  Elena Ruiz
Comment: Great chimney route with sketchy start. Nice warm-up.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Mirador
Comment: First attempt, pretty exploratory. I haven't enjoyed it as much, so not sure if this 7b will be my project.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Mirador
Comment: Super long route with the difficult part between the 4th and 5th bolts. Much easier than expected. I wouldn't say it's a 6b.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Mirador
Comment: Sent on the second attempt even though a hand hole broke at the anchor. I would say it's a soft 6c+. Watch out on the top part for unstable hand holes.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Mirador
Comment: Nice first attempt to understand and read the route. The first impressions is that it's not hard, but difficult to do it on-sight I would say.
Great route with two cruxes, where the second one (almost at the top) is the hardest one. Recommended route but your skin get destroyed after some attempts.
Great route, decently easy to read. Great underclings.
Great route, very enjoyable. The belaying zone though is a bit sketchy.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Sketchy start but after the 3rd bolt, it's all fine. The overhanging part is pretty cool. But I fell almost in the anchor due to stupid errors. Pretty sad but happy that I almost send an 7a on-sight.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Second attempt of this route, where I fell in the same place but I felt worse compared to the first attempt. Let's see if this one is sent one day.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: My first attempt to this 7b, a grade that I haven't sent yet, and pretty happy of the route. Decently easy to read with the hard part at the end with a crazy anchor, pretty difficult without the quickdraws set.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Oest - Vermell del Xincarró - El Vermell del Xincarró - Dreta
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Great route with the most difficult part on the 3rd bolt but easy to read, specially knowing that it's Montserrat.

Crag Path: Garraf - Pas de la Mala Dona - Neska Polita
Comment: Short route and very concentrated 7a, all between the second and the third bolt. I wasn't able to find the beta to be honest.

Crag Path: Garraf - Pas de la Mala Dona - Bauma
Comment: After one year later, I tried once again this route without much success. I felt a bit lost in the initial part, where it's more overhanging. It's true though that the second part looked better and I could handle it all in one go.

Crag Path: Garraf - Pas de la Mala Dona - Bauma
Comment: Comfortable 6a with great hand holds, all the time. Very cool route.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ferran Noguera

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: Super fun chimney route! Not gonna lie that it's a bit sandy, and it would be easier if the holds would have been cleaner but it's handleable.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: What a great route! Easy hand holes but a bit pumpy. If you manage correctly, it's pretty cool and handleable!

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: Nice route for warmup with high quality rock. Very nice!

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
With: Ribeiro di Janiero,  Quim Picó Mora,  Andreu Farré
Comment: 3rd and last attempt of the day. Everything was clear and the beta was well studied and I would say executed. However, I was super pumped and I fell just at the beginning of the crux.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
With: Ribeiro di Janiero,  Quim Picó Mora,  Andreu Farré

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
With: Ribeiro di Janiero,  Quim Picó Mora,  Andreu Farré
Comment: Good first attempt, preparing the route, where I could handle all the way up until the crux.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
With: Ribeiro di Janiero,  Quim Picó Mora,  Andreu Farré
Comment: Warm-up route for the day of today. Pretty cool, very recommended.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís
Comment: Difficult 6c in my opinion, but not worth a 6c hard. Fun start and crux on the overhanging part. If you know the beta is another story but still endurance is a key part.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís
Comment: Sketchy start and endurance route. The most difficult part is just before the tree from the top. Enjoying route!

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís
Comment: Great quality route. Fun start and intense last quickdraw, where endurance is important.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís,  Ana Mestre
Comment: 2nd attempt of the day, with quickdraws set, and fell in the same spot, but improved the beta. Let's see next day.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís,  Ana Mestre
Comment: The whole route is concentrated between the 3rd and 4th bolt, next to the big hole. It's a hard 6b+, pretty interesting.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís,  Ana Mestre
Comment: Fun 6a with a nice start. The last part, at the anchor, is a bit sketchy and where the most difficult part is.
Constant 7a except for an isolated movement in the middle part with small finger crimps (which are a bit slippery). The rest is easy knowing it's a 7a. A theoretical route I would say.
Fun route! A bit difficult to understand which are your bolts because there are a tone of routes in the same wall. Recommended to read the guide carefully before starting.
Great route with interesting movements in the middle part. The first part is a bit slippery but manageable. A bit harder than a plain 6b.
Great bavaresa! The first two bolts are a bit slippery but the rest is another story and very recommended.

What a fantastic route, extremely recommended! Fun and big overhanging and sketchy final part with small foot holds. Thank God though the quickdraws were already set. My first 7a on-sight, super happy!
Top tier route! Pretty long crag. It feels like it's never ending. Sometimes very scary but enjoyable anyway.

Fantastic route, I really enjoyed it! The first bolt is a bit far, but using the tree makes the path safe and easy enough. The most delicated part are on the first 3 bolts. The rest is easier. Anyway, the route is self explanatory.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os
Comment: Not very recommended route. We were a group of three people and none of us could read what to do between the 1st and 2nd bolts. Pretty crazy. The rest of the route is a 6b+ slab.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os
Comment: In the second attempt of the day I handled much better but I fell almost in the last movement of the route. Very sad but happy of how I handled all the rest.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os
Comment: After some weeks from the first attempt, I tried once again and I fell in a spot that I thought I had controlled. Then, the rest I handled correctly. Excited to try again.

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os
Comment: Great 6a route! The difficult part is at the beginning and at the end, but difficult at the 6a level. Nothing crazy.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís,  Andreu Farré
Comment: Happy to say that I was able to send on my second attempt after a proper rest. Knowing what to do and having the quickdraws set helps a lot.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís,  Andreu Farré
Comment: What a great route! Very sketchy start with slepery feet. After the 3rd bolt, it's handleable until you hit the overhanging part, which is pretty tiring. I fell in the overhanging part.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís,  Andreu Farré
Comment: I was able to send it on my second attempt! Very happy for the route. Very recommended with an interesting and fun start.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís,  Andreu Farré
Comment: Demanding starting on the first three bolts. The middle part is easy. The last part is a bit difficult but easier than the bottom part. I fell in my first attempt on the third bolt, almost at the end of the crux.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís,  Andreu Farré
Comment: The whole route is at the bottom part, in the first three bolts. The rest is pretty easy. You need to go left on the bottom part, try to not go to the 6b of the right.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ribeiro di Janiero,  Genís,  Andreu Farré
Comment: Nice route, nice 6a. Great for warm up, with some part of chimney very enjoyable.

After doing three routes today, this has been the best slab of the sector! The hardest part is at the bottom for sure. And, being honest, I could consider this as a red point since I had to go up and down three times for the first two moves, but since I haven't fallen, I'll consider it an on-sight.
Nice slab! There's no special crux, it's pretty balanced across the whole route.
Easy slab, nice for beginners. Easy because you can skip the slab several times using big rocks during the route.
Great route with the hard part on the top, or at least what I was able to read. The starting part, even though is the most overhanging, is easy.
Great route! Short and intense but with good rests in every bolt.
Great route! Decently easy to read with some hard movements, specially between the 4th and 5th bolts. Recommended.
Great hand holds and nice movements in the middle of the route. It's a 4, indeed, but it has some movements that might make your send a bit strange.

Horrible sandbag start not gonna lie. It's very polish, so it doesn't feel safe at all, specially knowing it's very close to the ground. The rest is another story but, because of the start, I wouldn't say it's a 6a.
Great and fun start but pretty tricky rest of the route. It's easy to get confused with the 6b+ from the right, as I did. Hard 6b+ not gonna lie.

Strange route not gonna lie. Big distance between the first bolts. I even had to use a rope between the first and second bolts to kinda have an extra bolt. It's a 6b but since I didn't feel great at the wall, I had to stop several times. Being honest, if you are new at the area like me, I wouldn't try this one.

Fantastic route, I really enjoyed it! Very sketchy beginning where it's pretty technical. Then you have a no hand rest and then the overhanging part, where it's okish. But I was a bit lost and pump, and couldn't handle the most difficult part. The end is pretty easy.
Great route! All movements were pretty clear and easy to read. However I fell in the anchor since I wasn't able to read correctly what to do. The whole route is easy, the crux in the last two bolts.
First route of the day on the first visit of Slovenia climbing. Wanted to go easy. Very recommended route for beginners.
I tried at the end of the day and pretty tired so not very sure if my opinion is fair enough. However, I saw it as a hard 6b. Pretty physical.
My first 7b attempt. The first half of the route is pretty easy and manageable. The second part is pretty tough but doable with good reading and a good strategy. We'll be back for more attempts!

I started this route thinking it was the neighbor 6b. Spoiler: I was wrong. It was very difficult because my mindset was centered for warming up and thinking it was a 6b. It's a great route but I wasn't at my best of the conditions. Warning: there's a huge rock at the very top of the route that it's not attached to the wall. Watch out!

I started this route for the warm-up of the session, but I decided to go down because I wasn't able to see the next bolt in the middle of the route, and I understood that I chose the wrong route (spoiler: I was wrong).
After a first failed attempt, I tried more from the right and it worked. Nice and difficult to read start.

The whole 7a is in the first two bolts, which is crazy and super intense. But I was able to do it in the second attempt! And the rest is pretty easy and straight forward! Happy to red point an other 7a!
First attempt done where part of the crux (the first two bolts) was done but I fell in the last part. Then, I decided to go down and start over.
Pretty hard start and difficult to read since there's no many combinations. However, we've seen a possible path going a bit right of the first bolts that looks promising.
Great slab for the first half of the route, which I don't feel it's a 6a, but not a 6a+, so let's say a 6a hard.
Another day, another try of this pretty overhanging route. I have the feeling that I did better this time but not so many more bolts done this time.
Nice route! Decently constant but specially hard on the middle, where I fell twice, the end part is pretty doable.
After the first try, and knowing what to do on the last but one bolt, I could send it.
First lead route of the day with a hard part at the last but one bolt, that couldn't manage/read correctly.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os
Comment: First route of the day and couldn't read anything after the first bolt and fell. Decided to go down and try again.
Great route! Couldn't handle an slippery foot but really wanted to come back for more tries.
Great route, manageable and good rests at the beginning. Pumpy last part.
Pumpy route from moment zero. Not trivial route at all. It's a 7a, but it's an special style.
Nice route. Pumpy for some moments, but manageable. Recommended route.
Pretty easy route. Easier than expected. Okay for warm-up.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os

Crag Path: Montserrat - Montserrat Nord-Est - Cova de l'Os

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 94. El Rovelló

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 26. Totxo del Boig
Comment: Interesting slab, where being tall is makes a huge different for topping out the boulder.

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 66. La Plaça

Crag Path: Margalef - Les Espadelles - Racó de les Espadelles
Comment: I chose this one for warm-up, and what a route. Not so self-explanatory route, but good for mental warm-up.
Another attempt of my big overhang wall and better compared to the previous (and first) attempt. I feel that I could send it next time.
What a great route! It looked difficult for being a 6c, and indeed it was. It was easy to read and you knew what to do at all time, but it was difficult anyway. Recommended route anyway.
Great route with rounded hands. Looked nice from the ground and indeed it was. Very recommended.
Cool route, nice for warming-up. A bit more pumpy than expected.

Comment: Very recommended boulder problem, one of my favorites of the session. Combination of power and technique. I couldn't flash it because of a stupid slip in my left foot. I changed my climbing shoes, so I could send it on my second attempt.

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 39. La Tanca
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: A boulder problem with two big jumps. Physical but with very good hands. I couldn't flash it because I failed in the second jump in my first attempt. A nice boulder problem though.

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 39. La Tanca
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: A better boulder problem compared to the right one (Massa fàcil). Using the tree next to the door, which is legal, makes the boulder a real 4+.

Crag Path: La Riba - Clot d'en Goda - 39. La Tanca
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Quim Picó Mora,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: My first boulder done in "real-life". An easy one, with very good hands but kinda too physical for being a simple 4. Not so ideal for warm-up.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Placa ecològica
With: Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Pure physical crag where the whole crux is in just three movements, in the very end of the route. I couldn't send it but very happy of the result.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Pasovich
With: Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Happy to red-point this crag. I would say is a solid 6b+ rather than 6b.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Pasovich
With: Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Crag where balance is pretty important. The difficult part is the middle, the rest is pretty doable. However, since the difficult part is more than a 5, I would say is  5+
I really enjoyed this one since it was mainly balance and not so strength. Very nice for the end of the day.
I really liked this one! Super easy to read and good holds. However, the overhanging is very decent and sending it requires more training from my side.
A nice/easy 7a where there's no much surprises in the holds. However balance and strength are pretty needed here.
Totally failed attempt because I was tired and my a bit injured finger wasn't helping. Anyway, I think is a nice route that we'll retry soon.
An interesting 6b+ where the holds are pretty special. Not so bad.
Not so successful attempt today at this one. Wall without overhanging but holds very small, so a good balance control is mandatory.
Very fun route with not so big holds but good enough for a 6c. I wasn't able to send it because I couldn't save all the power during the route. Any way, recommended.
Once again, another day, another attempt. And, once again, I was able to send it and I had to rest in the same bolt of the middle since I wasn't able to read it correctly.
Nice and expected 6b+. Nothing crazy, all holds were blunts.
After a season without climbing, good 6a for warm-up. No surprises and very readable.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: So happy to red point this! After some months of the last attempt, this is done!

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: Very fun route. Nothing special. More technical than physical.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: As always, one of my favorites crags in the zone. Very nice warm-up.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Quim Picó Mora,  Guillem Felis
Comment: Nice and special route. Holes are very round. A different type of route compared to the rest. Important to triple check each hold since there are multiple ways to hang from them.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Quim Picó Mora,  Guillem Felis
Comment: Very technical route, even though nothing crazier than a 6c. I almost on-sighted it but in the last but one bolt I didn't read it correctly, where there was a big volume on the left that was helpful to use.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Quim Picó Mora,  Guillem Felis
Comment: Nice warm-up route with some overhanging but very good holes.
Very recommended route, one of my favorites in the climbing gym! Not so intense in terms of power but very technical, where balance is crutial.

Very fun but also technical route, being my style. Balance is very important if you want to be efficient for the last part, where you need more power. Very happy to send my 6c+ on-sight. However, being honest with myself, it's an easier 6c+ than the average.
Nice 6b with pretty good hand holes but very physical. There's no much rest places during the route so being efficient is important.

The first part is okay. But then, when the overhanging part starts, it becomes a bit harder than a 7a in my opinion. Not so good hand holes knowing the grade marked and the overhang. I couldn't even finish it but worth a try anyway.

What an overhanging route. Very long part where being efficient is crutial if you want to send it. The holes are nice but there are sometimes that they are a bit far away, so you need some power. The reason why being efficient is a must.
Fun route with a bit of overhanging in the middle. Intuitive and even though looks physical, it's manageable.
Nice 6a+ for warm-up during today's session. Very intuitive and nothing crazy.

With: Ana Mestre,  Andreu,  Elena Ruiz,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: Pretty special route where the hands are all rounded. Very fun and recommended.

With: Ana Mestre,  Andreu,  Elena Ruiz,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: Another attempt today of a route I tried 3 weeks ago. Since it's very physical, and I wasn't at 100%, I couldn't send it.

With: Ana Mestre,  Andreu,  Elena Ruiz,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: Nice warm-up for today's session. Nothing crazy, a great 5c.

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Andreu,  Genís,  Guillem Felis
Comment: My first 6c on sight! Very technical route where balance is crucial, rather than power or strength. Very proud and happy for this crag!

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Andreu,  Genís,  Guillem Felis
Comment: Very surprised by this crag. It looked very physical and indeed it is, but applying good techniques it makes the crag easier. I wasn't able to on sight it because I got lost in the middle but I feel I'll red point it next day.

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Andreu,  Genís,  Guillem Felis
Comment: It's a 6c+, but what a 6c+! Very technical, physical and balance is crucial. Small holds and slippery feet. I abandoned the project but I feel I'll give a second chance in the future.

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Andreu,  Genís,  Guillem Felis
Comment: Technical route where you need to be very efficient for having enough strength during the full crag.

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Andreu,  Genís,  Guillem Felis
Comment: A nice crag with nice hands but decently physical in the middle, but doable and a classic 6b.

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Andreu,  Genís,  Guillem Felis
Comment: First crag of the day as a warm-up and for doing the course for getting the certificate for doing lead climbing on the gym.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Rototom
With: Quim Picó Mora,  Ana Mestre,  Guillem Felis
Comment: After some months of the first try, I fell in the same damn spot. Actually, three times. I'll try to do it again another day.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Rototom
With: Quim Picó Mora,  Ana Mestre,  Guillem Felis
Comment: Super fun and nice crag, long enough and very easy to read. The crux is almost in the end.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: One of my favorites crags in La Cascada. There's only one serious crux between the third and forth bolt. But once you seen in, it's doable to red point it.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: Nice and fun crux, also very physical, in the last but one bolt.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: Nice warm-up of today's session where the crux is in the last but one bolt.
Very fun crag where the hands are great but it's easy to get lost id you don't read it. I felt because a foot broke between the last and last but one bolts.
Compared to the previous attempt, better but still far away to send it.
An interesting conglomerate crag where the beginning (first 2 bolts) and the last but one bolt are pretty difficult to read and small hands. I felt in these two parts.
Interesting conglomerate type of crag with decent pockets and very easy to read. It's all fine where the final part is the one most difficult to read. Well equipped and with a carabinier on the top.
A nice definition of a conglomerate, where it's definitely not something I'm use to. I felt in the last but one bolt, where the most difficult part is.
A fun crag with a overhanging part, where the crux was. However, reading the route well, it's pretty possible to send it. Very recommended crag.
In the same session I was able to red-point it. The crux of the crag is the first two bolts, the rest is fine. But, because of the beginning, I would say is a 6a+.
The first two bolts were pretty challenging, and doing it in sight was difficult. The reason why, after doing that part, I decided to go down and try it again for the ground.
The first bolt is pretty far, but doesn't feel unsafe. The crag is, in my opinion, more difficult than the grade given. It's a 5c+/6a for me.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís
Comment: Nice route with a fun chimney, but with a lot of sand and spiders, making the route more difficult than expected. So, it's a 6a+ hard for me.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís
Comment: Interesting crag where the hands are very round, very different than the type of crags of this area. I would consider a 6A hard though.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís
Comment: A wonderful super long crag that I enjoyed a lot! Really good hands and clear movements but very long, so being efficient is crutial.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís
Comment: Nice chimney with a lot of sand. Easy but you have to know how to handle chimneys.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís
Comment: Nice crag for warm-up with the crux in the middle. An standard 6a+ which no many surprises.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: Last crag of the day enjoying it as its full. This second time I dit it (last time was some months ago), I can confirm that it's an actual 6A rather than 5+.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: Finally I was able to send it from the ground! Super happy about it! After 8 attempts, I have all the movements in my head, so it was pretty doable today

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: Nice route with a combination of different types of climbing. Fun meanwhile I was warming up for this session. However, I would say is a 6a+ hard.

Meanwhile visiting The Burren we realized, by surprise, that there was a wall full of routes to be climbed. Since we weren't bringing any material, I decided to climb this one like a "souvenir" from the area. Pretty easy and fun solo route.

Totally unexpected experience since we were planning to only hike Errigal. However, we found a person around the route very fan of scrambling and he recommended us this route, along with Tower Ridge (which we didn't do it).

We've decided to do it as is (without rope) since it felt always super safe. I think today we discovered a new passion, combining hiking and climbing: scrambling.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: I was almost able to handle the difficult part and sending it but I step into the rope and I slipped, just when I was able to do the difficult movement. Anyway, next time.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: Another failure because I forgot again the crux of the crag, but this time I focused for remembering for next time.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: Another attempt but I forgot how to handle the difficult part, so I decided to go down and try again

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
Comment: Another attempt to the project today. Even though I wasn't able to send it, I felt more confident this time.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: Most of the route is pretty easy except for the crux, between the 4th and 5th bolts, where the 6c is all concentrated. Tiny hands there where the theory is very important.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
Comment: Nice route for warm-up with an easy hands. Also, pretty safe during the whole route.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: A fun beginning where using the tree nearby is must (not sure what's going to happen with this crag if that tree one day is gone). The rest is pretty nice, where the balance is by far more important than strength.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: A pretty interesting beginning with an slippery part. Make sure to go left after the third bolt, if not you could start with the neighbor 6b.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: A beautiful chimney where the feet is very important for sending the crag. Even though the bolts are a bit separated, it feels pretty safe.

With: Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Genís,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: Very long and fun crag, very recommended for warm-up. Nice views on the top!

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Andreu
Comment: I tried for the second time in the same day, and I was able to do a bit more but still I wasn't able to do the hard part.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Andreu
Comment: Another try, the first one of the day, for familiarizing the crag once again. I'll try once again, and now for real, later.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Andreu
Comment: Not a 6b+ in my opinion, more an 6b than anything else. Incredible good hands but some slippery feet at the beginning. Then, a nice ending.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
With: Genís,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Andreu
Comment: Nice warm-up with an easy beginning. Important to go left in last but one bolt for making it easier.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada

Comment: From the 3rd to the 6th bolt it's pretty difficult in terms of technique and physic. I was about to complete it hang it, but I needed to rest in almost every single move of the difficult part. I realized I need more practice to try to send this one.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
With: Quim Picó Mora,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: I gave another try in the same day but I fell in the same point. However, I felt more comfortable than last time so I have the hope that this crag will be my first 6c sent.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
With: Quim Picó Mora,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: Pretty interesting route. An easy beginning and ending, but the difficult part is in the middle in just two bolts, where the foot is good but the hands are pretty tiny, but doable after knowing the beta.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
With: Quim Picó Mora,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: After falling between the first and second bolt, where the 6b is, I was able to send it going a bit to the right using a inverted hand. After the 4th bolt, it's pretty easy with a wonderful layback. Super fun route and very recommended.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - La Cascada
With: Quim Picó Mora,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: I fell between the first and the second bolt since I wasn't able to see the beta (or at least my beta). I decided to go down and try it from scratch.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - La Cascada - El Soldat Romà
With: Quim Picó Mora,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera
Comment: Nice route for warming-up, pretty easy beggining with a nice ending. Very well equipped.

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Guillem Felis,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment:
The first pitch is all good, and the 6b+ is more physical than technical, even some parts of campus. A nice and fun boulder problem that I'll try again. However, it's pretty dangerous since the one under cannot see you.
1:
2:

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Guillem Felis,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: All it's an easy 5+ but the beginning is pretty tricky for being a 5+, but pretty cool anyways!

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Guillem Felis,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: I've done a wrong movement in the third bolt, which made hang at that point. The route is extremely physical for being a 6A, so I would say is a 6A+. Actually, the whole sector is more difficult that the registered grade.

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís,  Guillem Felis,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: It has a pretty tricky beginning along with the the last but one bolt, which it's interesting. I would say is a more 5+ than a 5 (actually, the whole sector).

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  David Aleu Moseguí,  Guillem Felis
Comment: Each bolt are pretty far away from each other, so being strong in mind is vital for sending this route.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  David Aleu Moseguí,  Guillem Felis
Comment:
Indeed, there are only 4 bolts and what a 4 bolts. I wasn't able to send it, even resting, since after the second bolt is crazy.

Aside from this, as a comment, the first bolt is super far away.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  David Aleu Moseguí,  Guillem Felis
Comment: It's very important to keep your right hand pretty close to the neighbor 6A and using the right hand to pass the rope. Pretty difficult and tiny holes, specially from the second bolt. However, I would say it's possible.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  David Aleu Moseguí,  Guillem Felis
Comment: A classic 6b+ with very predinticable movements, very physicals though. I was able to send it because it was the second one of the day.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ana Mestre,  Genís,  Elena Ruiz,  David Aleu Moseguí,  Guillem Felis
Comment: The first two bolts are pretty crazy, very scary if you are not prepared. However, a very fun route even though I consider it a 6A hard.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: A very physical crag where was pretty difficult for me to send it all together where I rest/fall in 3 places. I like it but I've done 6b+ I enjoyed more.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: I tried in the same attempt like 5 times the first movement, which is pretty crazy. After knowing my beta, I decided to go to the ground for trying the red point.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: A wonderful route where the beginning is pretty difficult from a theory point of view, but since it's from the ground it's easy to study it. It's super fun, very recommended.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: An easy starting with a wonderful, and very physical, layback in the last bolt that makes, in my opinion, a 6A hard route.

With: Marc Klingenberg,  Ferran Noguera,  Ribeiro di Janiero
Comment: A nice 6A for warm-up. The type of wall is fantastic, where nothing is slippery.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Wild west
With: Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís
Comment: I tried again this crag being focus in sending the difficult part (between 4th and 5th bolts). However, I wasn't able to do it and just before falling I grabbed the quick draw. After this, the rest was fine and very fun! This could be red pointed for sure next day.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Wild west
With: Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís
Comment: I fell between the 4th and 5th bolts, where the level is. After that, I realized my knot wasn't 100% as I wanted. So, just as a piece of mind, I decided to go down.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Pasovich
With: Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís
Comment: Very similar to the neighbor crag, but a bit simpler, but a 6B anyways. Very fun crag!

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Pasovich

Comment: A beautiful 6B, with different types of techniques. However, I fell in the last but one bolt without clipping it; so I had the most spectacular fall until today; around 6 meters.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Vegetarian
With: Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís
Comment: The beginning is pretty doable, being a 5+, but the final part is where the 6A is. Nothing crazy though.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Vegetarian
With: Ana Mestre,  Marc Klingenberg,  Elena Ruiz,  Genís
Comment: A standard 5+, nice for warm-up. Greats hands and feet. The distance though between each bolt is considerable.

With: Ana Mestre,  Andreu,  Elena Ruiz,  Ferran Noguera,  José Ignacio Bustamante Vargas,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment:
I tried this at 6PM and the rock was freezing. Because of this I fell in the second bolt since I wasn't able to feel anything on my fingers. After warming up them, I was able to complete the first two pitches until the 6b. However, this is a 6a+ in my opinion.

2:[6b]

With: Ana Mestre,  Elena Ruiz,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg,  Andreu,  José Ignacio Bustamante Vargas

Crag Path: Valle del Sarca - Massone - Settore A

An easy beginning but then a super slippery part where it becomes pretty difficult. Then, after that, there's a decent slope where the hands are pretty good but they are a bit far away, where confidence is the key. The last part is good and self-explanatory.

We'll see if red-pointing this is going to be possible, but we'll try for sure.

Crag Path: Cervello - Vallirana - Les casetes d'en Muntaner - Est Esquerra - Pasovich

With: Ana Mestre,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: The very beginning is pretty difficult for being a 6A+ in my opinion, but the antepenultimate bolt is by far nothing that I would grade as 6A+. It's one of the most physical routes I've ever done and, in the end, after 3 or 4 attempts hanging from the antepenultimate bolt, I wasn't able to complete it.

With: Ana Mestre,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: After two attempts on the same day and a proper rest, I was able to red-point this route making sure to be super focused and not make any mistakes in the two crucial parts (between the first and second bolt and in the penultimate bolt). I would summarize this route as a nice combination of different climbing techniques. Very recommended.

With: Ana Mestre,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: Just next to the previous attempt, I was able to pass the first of the two crucial parts but I fell in the second one because of too much fatigue. In the second part there as three finger pocket that is mandatory to use if you want to complete it.

With: Ana Mestre,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: I fell between the first and the second bolt, which is the first of the two crucial parts of the route. The rock in this part is quite scratchy but there are a few holes that you can use. It is important to study this part well before starting from below.

With: Ana Mestre,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: A proper 6A without many difficulties. In the same way as its neighbor (Barrufet), using the feet correctly makes the route easier.

With: Ana Mestre,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: The whole route is a 6A without many difficult parts but the very last part (between the last and penultimate bolts) is pretty difficult. I wouldn't have done it without guidance or a beta suggestion.

With: Ana Mestre,  Ferran Noguera,  Marc Klingenberg
Comment: Very fun 5+ where using your feet is essential for doing without much effort
